Time Series Forecasting - California Electricity Demand¶

This notebook analyzes a real-world electricity demand dataset built from publicly available renewable and weather data published by CAISO and NREL. The authors (Ortega et al. 2023) compiled the datasets into a single, five-minute resolution time series that reflects actual California grid behavior.

The outcome variable is total electricity demand in MW, and I will study the following explanatory variables:

Attribute Description Unit
Season Season (1=Winter, 2=Spring, 3=Summer, 4=Autumn) categorical
Day_of_the_week Day of week (0=Monday 6=Sunday) categorical
Temperature Air temperature C
PV_production Solar energy production MW

I explore the demand signal and qualifying variables to identify trends and seasonal structure in Section 1. I then fit an OLS regression on these explanatory variables in Section 2. In Section 3, I build a hybrid model that combines OLS with a SARIMA model fitted to the OLS residualsthis approach captures both the linear relationships with exogenous variables and any remaining temporal autocorrelation patterns. Throughout the analysis, I employ standard time-series practices including time-aware train/test splits, stationarity checks, and residual diagnostics. I demonstrate a clear, interpretable forecasting workflow on real energy data, comparing model performance to identify the most effective approach.

Setup¶

All analysis is conducted using base R and standard time series packages.

Load the Dataset¶

Here I load the dataset, preparing the time index, dropping rows with null values, and aggregating to an hourly resolution. The original 5-minute resolution is more granular than necessary for this analysis, and hourly resolution is sufficient for observing trends throughout the day.

In [53]:
# Load CSV 
dat <- suppressWarnings(
    read_csv("./data/Database.csv", 
                locale = locale(encoding = "UTF-8"),
                show_col_types = FALSE 
               )
    )

# Convert to time series object and aggregate to hourly resolution
dat_ts <- dat %>% 
    mutate(Time = ymd_hm(Time)) %>%
    drop_na() %>%  # Drop rows with null values
    mutate(Time = floor_date(Time, "1 hour")) %>%
    group_by(Time) %>%
    summarise(
      Electric_demand = mean(Electric_demand, na.rm = TRUE),
      Temperature = mean(Temperature, na.rm = TRUE),
      PV_production = mean(PV_production, na.rm = TRUE),
      Season = first(Season),
      Day_of_the_week = first(Day_of_the_week),
      .groups = "drop"
    ) %>%
    as_tsibble(index = Time)

1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

1.1 Outcome: Electricity Demand¶

Total electricity demand over the dataset shows strong seasonal patterns in both daily and yearly frequencies. Key drivers include temperature-driven needs for space heating and cooling, which create strong summer afternoon peaks and winter morning/evening peaks. This is alongside predictable daily cycles tied to work, leisure, and household schedules. These factors help explain why grid engineers must carefully balance supply to match fluctuating demand across hours, days, and seasons.

Summarize seasonal cycles by year by averaging monthly demand over the 3 years in the dataset. In 2020, the summer peak was higher than both 2019 and 2021, possibly reflecting the indoor air conditioning needs of those in isolation/quarantine during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The decomposition reveals substantial seasonal and trend components, suggesting that a purely regression-based approach may leave temporal structure in the residuals.

I visualize the relationship between electricity demand and two major driving variables: outside temperature and solar energy production. Temperature shows a visible association with demand, consistent with heating and cooling usage. This relationship also has a non-constant slope, motivating the inclusion of a temperature-squared term in the model. Solar production has a less clear relationship with demand, and is also influenced by temperature. It is included as more of a control variable rather than a direct driver of demand.

2. Time Series Regression¶

OLS provides a transparent baseline that quantifies the linear relationship between the demand and the observed predictors. Categorical variables are encoded to capture calendar effects.

2.1 Estimate OLS with Lagged Features¶

Feature engineering:

In [63]:
# Create time series features for regression
dat_ts_reg <- dat_ts %>%
  mutate(
    # Time-based features
    hour_of_day = hour(Time),
    month = month(Time),
    year = year(Time),
    # Lagged demand (1 hour back)
    lag1_demand = lag(Electric_demand, 1),
    # Convert categorical variables to factors
    Season = as.factor(Season),
    Day_of_the_week = as.factor(Day_of_the_week),
    hour_of_day = as.factor(hour_of_day)
  ) %>%
  drop_na() # Remove rows with NA from lagging

Split data into training and test sets, using last 7 days (1 hour interval * 24 hours/day * 7 days = 168 observations) as the test set.

In [88]:
acf(residuals(model_ts_reg))

The strong performance of OLS suggests that the relationship between electric demand and the exogenous variables (temperature, PV production, season, day of week) is primarily linear, however there is significant autocorrelation left in the residuals of the OLS model.

This motivates the use of SARIMA models in Section 3, which are specifically designed to handle temporal autocorrelation.

3. SARIMA Model¶

To address residual autocorrelation, I fit a SARIMA model to the OLS residuals. This hybrid approach separates the explainable linear variation (captured by OLS) from the remaining time-dependent structure (captured by SARIMA).

3.1 Model Development and Selection¶

An ADF test on the residuals suggests stationarity, supporting the use of a SARIMA model:

In [72]:
# Extract residuals from OLS model and prepare as tsibble
ols_residuals <- dat_train %>%
  mutate(residuals = residuals(model_ts_reg)) %>%
  select(Time, residuals) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Time)

# Check stationarity of residuals using ADF test
cat("Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test for Stationarity:\n")
adf_test <- tseries::adf.test(ols_residuals$residuals, alternative = "stationary")
cat("ADF Statistic:", round(adf_test$statistic, 4), "\n")
cat("p-value:", round(adf_test$p.value, 4), "\n")
if(adf_test$p.value < 0.05) {
  cat("Result: Residuals are stationary (p < 0.05)\n\n")
} else {
  cat("Result: Residuals may be non-stationary (p >= 0.05)\n\n")
}

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test for Stationarity:

p-value smaller than printed p-value

ADF Statistic: -15.3871 
p-value: 0.01 
Result: Residuals are stationary (p < 0.05)

The final forecast is obtained by combining the OLS predictions with SARIMA forecasts of the residuals:

In [73]:
LOAD_MODEL <- TRUE

if (LOAD_MODEL) {
    # Load the saved SARIMA model
    sarima_model <- readRDS("outputs/sarima_on_residuals.rds")
    cat("Loaded saved SARIMA model\n")
} else {
    # Fit SARIMA model on residuals using automatic model selection
    cat("Fitting SARIMA model on OLS residuals using stepwise search...\n")
    
    sarima_model <- ols_residuals %>%
      model(
        # Season period = 24 for daily patterns in hourly data
        sarima = ARIMA(residuals ~ PDQ(period = 24))
      )
    
    # Save the model output
    saveRDS(sarima_model, "outputs/sarima_on_residuals.rds")
    cat("\nModel fitting complete and saved.\n")
}

3.2 Model Diagnostics and Residual Analysis¶

Compute $R^2$, $R^2_{adjusted}$, and AIC from the SARIMA model.

In [75]:
# Build hybrid model predictions (OLS + SARIMA on residuals)
sarima_aug <- augment(sarima_model, new_data = ols_residuals)
sarima_stats <- glance(sarima_model)

# Combine OLS predictions with SARIMA residual predictions for hybrid model
hybrid_train <- dat_train %>%
  mutate(
    ols_pred = predict(model_ts_reg),
    sarima_resid_pred = sarima_aug$.fitted,
    hybrid_pred = ols_pred + sarima_resid_pred
  )

# Calculate R for the hybrid model
hybrid_r2 <- 1 - sum((hybrid_train$Electric_demand - hybrid_train$hybrid_pred)^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
  sum((hybrid_train$Electric_demand - mean(hybrid_train$Electric_demand, na.rm = TRUE))^2, na.rm = TRUE)

hybrid_n <- nrow(hybrid_train)
hybrid_p <- sarima_model %>% tidy() %>% nrow()
hybrid_adj_r2 <- 1 - (1 - hybrid_r2) * ((hybrid_n - 1) / (hybrid_n - hybrid_p - 1))

cat("Hybrid Model (OLS + SARIMA) Statistics:\n")
cat("R-squared:", round(hybrid_r2, 4), "\n")
cat("Adjusted R-squared:", round(hybrid_adj_r2, 4), "\n")
cat("SARIMA component AIC:", round(sarima_stats$AIC, 2), "\n")

Adjusted R-squared: 0.9981 
SARIMA component AIC: 354106.7

3.3 Forecasting and Evaluation¶

Generate hybrid forecasts (OLS + SARIMA on residuals):

In [82]:
# Step 1: Get OLS predictions for validation set
ols_val_predictions <- predict(model_ts_reg, newdata = dat_val)

# Step 2: Prepare validation residuals data for SARIMA forecasting
val_residuals <- dat_val %>%
  select(Time) %>%
  mutate(residuals = NA_real_) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Time)

# Step 3: Forecast residuals using SARIMA
sarima_forecast_obj <- sarima_model %>%
  forecast(new_data = val_residuals) %>%
  as_tibble()

# Step 4: Combine OLS + SARIMA forecasts for hybrid predictions
dat_val <- dat_val %>%
  mutate(
    ols_pred = as.numeric(ols_val_predictions),
    sarima_resid_forecast = as.numeric(sarima_forecast_obj$.mean),
    hybrid_forecast = ols_pred + sarima_resid_forecast
  )

Examine the performance of the hybrid model on the test set:

In [89]:
# Calculate test set metrics
hybrid_test_metrics <- dat_val %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  summarise(
    mae = mean(abs(Electric_demand - hybrid_forecast), na.rm = TRUE),
    rmse = sqrt(mean((Electric_demand - hybrid_forecast)^2, na.rm = TRUE)),
    mape = mean(abs((Electric_demand - hybrid_forecast) / Electric_demand), na.rm = TRUE) * 100
  )

cat("Hybrid Model Forecast Performance (test set):\n")
cat("MAE:", round(hybrid_test_metrics$mae, 2), "MW\n")
cat("RMSE:", round(hybrid_test_metrics$rmse, 2), "MW\n")
cat("MAPE:", round(hybrid_test_metrics$mape, 2), "%\n\n")

# Compare to OLS-only model
mae_improvement <- (ols_val_metrics$mae - hybrid_test_metrics$mae) / ols_val_metrics$mae * 100
rmse_improvement <- (ols_val_metrics$rmse - hybrid_test_metrics$rmse) / ols_val_metrics$rmse * 100

cat("The hybrid model achieves a", round(mae_improvement, 1), "% improvement in MAE and", 
    round(rmse_improvement, 1), "% improvement in RMSE compared to the OLS-only model,\n")
cat("demonstrating the value of modeling residual autocorrelation.\n")

4. Takeaways¶

  • Electricity demand contains both explainable structure and strong temporal dependence.
  • OLS regression captures calendar and weather effects but leaves autocorrelation in the residuals.
  • Modeling residuals with SARIMA improves forecasts without sacrificing interpretability.
  • Time-aware validation and residual diagnostics are essential for time series modeling.
